To summarize results, we applied an integrative approach that targets the overall climate response of a population to determine whether it is mainly dependent on the energy conferred by temperature, or the availability of water conferred by precipitation. This is essentially achieved by averaging out seasonal responses that can have opposite signs52. The seasonal CStraits were summarized as8Climatelim.gp=∑i=1nTempCStraitsTemp.igp−∑i=1nSMICStraitsSMI.igp−∑i=1nSnowCStraitsSnow.igp\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{Climate}}_{{\mathrm{lim.gp}}} = {\mathop {\sum}\limits_{i = 1}^{n{\mathrm{Temp}}} {{\mathrm{CStraits}}_{{\mathrm{Temp}}}{\mathrm{.igp}}}} - {\mathop {\sum}\limits_{i = 1}^{n{\mathrm{SMI}}} {{\mathrm{CStraits}}_{{\mathrm{SMI}}{\mathrm{.igp}}}}} - {\mathop {\sum}\limits_{i = 1}^{n{\mathrm{Snow}}} {{\mathrm{CStraits}}_{{\mathrm{Snow}}{\mathrm{.igp}}}}}$$\end{document}where Climatelim is the overall NPP climate response, and Temp, SMI, and Snow represent respectively the set of n significant seasonal CStraits for temperature, soil moisture index, and snowfall. Negative values of Climatelim are associated with low energy limitation and high water limitation on NPP; positive values are indicative of high energy limitation and low water limitation on NPP.
